President Zuma has written to Shaun Abrahams asking him why he shouldn&#8217;t be suspended pending an inquiry into his fitness to hold office. JOHANNESBURG Freedom Under Law has welcomed President Jacob Zuma s letter to National Prosecuting Authority head Shaun Abrahams in which he asks him to give reasons why he should not be suspended.The letter, sent on Monday, is included in Abrahams s response to FUL and the Helen Suzman Foundation's court application to have him suspended. FUL s Piet Olivier says: We want the president to follow through and suspend them and for them to be removed for a parliamentary inquiry but we are very happy that the first steps has been taken.Earlier on Tuesday, Eyewitness News revealed Abrahams s response to a court application brought by FUL and the Helen Suzman Foundation to have him suspended as the National Director of Public Prosecutions. Included in his response are a heated exchange of letters, between him and Berning Ntlameza that reveal the Hawks anger at the NPA head s decision to withdraw the controversial charges against Finance Minister Pravin Gordhan. The suspension application is due to be heard by a full bench of the high court in Pretoria next week. Read the NDPP's answering affidavit in the application to have him suspended: NDPP Answering Aff by Primedia Broadcasting on Scribd(Edited by Masechaba Sefularo)